The game is relatively good and I do recommend it despite the grind system in place.

Pros:
- has good graphics;
- the story is good and entertaining;
- the game mechanics are interesting and engaging ;
- you have a bit of freedom of doing different questlines however you want;
Cons:
- it's very grindy and repetitive; you have to capture 4 fortresess in order to advance the main story; while it sounds easy enough keep in mind that you have to: dominate captains from the defending fortress, you have to level up yourself in order of having a chance of figthing against captains/warchiefs/overlords and you have to set up warchiefs (4) in the fortress so you can capture the assault points faster; all this while being ambushed by other captains or follower orcs who betray you; oh, I almost forgot to mention that you have to keep in mind what strengths/weaknesses the captains/warchiefs/overlords have in order to avoid enraging them;
- the capturing of the fortresses feels tedious and boring, because the amount of time you need to put in capturing them;
- the capturing of the fortresses is approximately 3/4 of the game;
- cartoonish jokes which felt that they didn't belonged in the game's settings; though this isn't such a big issues, I felt it needed to be said;

I honestly took a 1 month break, when I found out that I need to take 3 more fortresses to advance the story, but the captains/warchiefs/overlords were 15-20+ levels above me. 

Galadriel's blade storyline was somewhat entertaining and it provides a continuation of Talion's story. It was a bit awkward, with a mix of cartoonish orcs/jokes and modern feminist cliches. The end boss's background felt like it was written by the Rings of Powers writers.

The Desolation of Mordor is more of a standalone expansion, it's the story of Balanor after he and Talion part ways. It offers a fresh new skills, revigorating the combat system, since Baranor doesn't have a wraith/ring of power/light of Galadriel powers. Also, the capturing of the fortress felt more natural and less grinding. In terms of story, I have some issues with a few things, but they aren't very notable.
